We review goodwill for impairment annually in the fourth quarter of the fiscal year and whenever events or changes in
circumstances indicate that the carrying value of goodwill might not be recoverable. The impairment test for goodwill
involves calculating the fair value of each reporting unit and comparing that value to the carrying value. If the fair value
of the reporting unit is less than its carrying value, the difference is recorded as a goodwill impairment charge, not to
exceed the total amount of goodwill allocated to that reporting unit. During the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2021, we
conducted our annual goodwill impairment test and determined that the fair value of all our reporting units exceeded
their carrying value.
